Juan Manuel Alvarez was convicted of causing a deadly train crash in Los Angeles.
Prosecutors argued he did it for attention, while defense claimed it was a suicide attempt gone wrong.
Alvarez apologized for the disaster, stating he never meant to harm anyone.
His troubled past, including abuse and methamphetamine addiction, was highlighted in court.
The jury recommended life in prison without parole, with prosecutors seeking the death penalty.
Alvarez's family testified about the violence and trauma he endured growing up.
The tragic incident left 11 dead, sparking a legal battle for justice and closure for the victims' families.
